okay I hope you can hear me if I talk about this same level this is this is Tuesday February 7 I believe it is and we're in the Clayton Williams building and I have the

honor and pleasure of chatting with buck henderson about his a m years but to begin with describe your life before you enrolled here family where what did they do for a living where'd you grow up where'd you go to high school give us a biography before you got here as a fish yes sir uh started i was born in 1940 and
Jacksboro, Texas, which is located between Fort Worth and Wichita Falls.
I guess you'd call it a small, ranching, oil field community.

And like most of the kids that I graduated with in 1958, we went from the first grade through high school together and grew up from that standpoint of you had to be very careful what you did and how you treated people because you had to live with that all your life.
And I guess my emphasis was I was in the Scouts until I was 18 years old.
I think the main reason I stayed in the Scouts was because we ushered all the TCU football games.
So for seven years, I never missed a Saturday when there was a
home game at TCU.
We were 60 miles away.
My emphasis in high school, I guess, was sports.
I played football, basketball, golf, and tennis, and wasn't any good in any of them, but in a small town you got to play.
My weakness was academics.
My mother died when I was very young.
I was raised by my grandmother.
My father was a rancher, and so I was pretty well

Raised as I say by my grandmother and my aunt who stayed after my mother died the eighth grade until I graduated and so I was a young man who probably got out of the door of high school because My two toughest subjects my teacher had also taught or my teachers had taught my father so I
That kind of sums it up.
How many in the senior class?
In senior class, we had 60, of which Texas A&M was an all-boys class, I mean an all-boys school.
I think we had 31 boys, and we had six of those 30 that started A&M.
Five of us graduated, which was unbelievable.
The one that didn't graduate left the first week and went to Texas Tech and graduated from there.
So again, when I came to A&M that year, they had made the Corps compulsory.
And so of those five that stayed, two had handicap-type problems, which they didn't have to be in the Corps.
Why did you come to A&M?
Why here instead of some other place?
I think there were two reasons.
One of the reasons was I mentioned the football game at a TCU football game.
I believe it was probably 1952, 53.
A&M was playing TCU that day, and A&M may have only won three games that year.
But a quarterback by the name of Don Ellis ran wild.
He was All-Southwest Conference quarterback, I remember, or I'm pretty sure he was, but he put on a one-man show, and they upset TCU.

I took my little autograph book, which I had, and took it down to the dressing room, and one of the trainers took me in, and I got to meet the quarterback, and he put, best wishes, Don Ellis to Quincy, Louisiana, and I've been fortunate enough
in recent years to get to know Colonel Ellis, and I think that had probably the start of my looking towards A&M.

The second reason was the guy that pretty well was my godfather was Henry Richards, class of 41, and I caddied for him for about six years, and he used to bring four of us down here for the football game, actually bring five,
sometimes because he had six tickets, and he'd bring us to the games.
We'd get home late on those Saturday nights after the game, but he kept never pushing, but he was a role model in our little community.
So you came a number of times to the campus.
I came probably to
When I was in high school, I probably came down here for I'd say six football games.

The first one that I came to was that famous TCU rain game where A&M won seven to six when Swink was playing for TCU and Crow and Lloyd Taylor kicked that extra point in the 100-hour windstorm, all of that.
The tornado hit outside Bryan that day.
Now, I'm assuming that you are not from a family of old education, like I'm not either.
No.
What caused you to think that you had a chance to go to college?
Well, I think I grew up and just assumed that I would always go.
Both of my two older sisters went, and neither one of them finished.
They went to TCU, and after a couple of years, one transferred to North Texas, but they never completed their degrees.
They went on to work.

I just, because of, I think, Mr. Richards, Henry Richards, who I'm still very close with, who has also been a very good supporter of the A&M golf team, I think I came here and just figured, well, Jacksonboro was probably a pretty well-to-do town per capita because of all of the oil and everything, and I just...
I always knew I was going to come, but in the back of my mind, I was always worried that could I make it because, as I said, I really got out the door of high school barely.
What had impressed you about A&M before you came to them all?

I think one of the things, as I mentioned, I'd been in the Boy Scouts for all those years, and I think you look in the Scouts, something about discipline, and you look at possibility for leadership because you work your way up.
and then also helping other people.
And then you go back and you looked at A&M.
I think if I'd been from a big city and had come down here, I don't know if I would have looked favorably on it.
I looked at this as just kind of a neat experience because the bottom line,
Everybody was basically the same in your class, you know.
There wasn't a fish camp then, was there?
There was not a fish camp, but it kind of makes it sound like I wasn't a very good student the way I've led into this so far.
But I will be very honest, my senior year I saw that I had to have chemistry and I had to have plain geometry to get into Texas A&M.
And I made a 70 in chemistry, and you can guess what I made in plain geometry, a 70.
So I knew that I had a very weak background in the training for academics.
So the bottom line was I had the opportunity to go to Junction that summer, which was for students that wanted to go to work on some of their academic skills.
And so I chose to go, and I did go one semester at Junction.
And I think that definitely helped me because
They did emphasize study hall, and they had help sessions, and then I came.

Of course, I'll go a step further and say when I got here, they also had something called the basic division, which I took advantage of, and again, I think I knew, and maybe the good thing, I knew that I had some weaknesses.
describe the junction annex and as far as you know about how long had it been going i'm i'm really not sure i think it'd been going in maybe a different type of environment prior to becoming a a
I guess you'd say an academic enhancement program for incoming freshmen.
You went out there.
It was tough.
You took normally seven hours of PE and two other classes.
And I remember that we lived in tents.
And to me, it was just like scout camp all over again.
And you did it alphabetically.
And some of those guys that I got to know there are still ones that you are involved with today.
Such as?
Such as, I'll take Bo Martin is a very good friend of mine now in Dallas.
I think probably the thing that I learned right there, well, I'll give you an example.
There is a gentleman here that I still, you might want to stop in just one second, I see.
I'll think of Eddie's name in a second, and then you'll really see how bad I am.
But he's moved back to Bryan the other day, and the first thing he did, he came up to me and he said, now I get a chance to beat you.
And so I asked him, what do you mean?
He said, well, you won the intramural ping pong out there, and I was runner up, and you beat me three to two.
And I said, well, I don't remember any of that.
But I think, again, it's just one of those moments
areas where you get to meet a lot of people.
I bought a car from Gerald Headings a few years ago that lives up about 30 miles out of Dallas.
And we shared bunks with each other.
And so you could probably name 15 different guys that you've had.
Were there some teachers you recall positively from that time?
Mr. Perry, I remember, was very, very outstanding that I had him in math.
I just thought that was excellent.
What was the other course you had?
I had English.
Both of them, I believe, were Dr. Perry and Dr. Kane.
And PE was just a general one-hour conditioning class.

it was uh very tough and i think probably it was very good for me for one reason uh it was structured and uh you know you can go back and read the junction boys and you you see how structured it was well it was pretty structured on us out there too and we had lights out and uh there's certain things that we were able to do describe the typical a day the typical day was we'd get up in the in the morning seemed like we had to whistle jock same as we had in the core and this was all good training for the core
And then we'd have to be up, we'd go to breakfast, and we were expected to keep our tents clean.
We didn't have inspections and things like that.
And probably one of the things I remember most, you'd go to breakfast, and then you had three classes during the day.
And a lot of emphasis was put on academics, so it did mean that the studying that night, the tents,
you had to keep the noise level down.
And quite interesting because it was pretty warm down there on a summer night.
But it was a good adjustment for coming into, which was a very big shock for me,
entering the Corps of Cadets and being a fish because I was not prepared for that at all.
And you see that, as you look back on it, as a positive preparation for you?
Oh, definitely.
Definitely.
Because I think, number one, a lot of people
had never had to, maybe they didn't have a brother, maybe they came from families that had money also.
In other words, they'd never had tight living conditions as such.
Sure, you go to church camp or you'd go to, as I mentioned earlier, scout camp, but it was usually never where you would have maybe 16 guys in one tent.
So it was a
peer pressure because you always had, I came from being very, very reserved, and we had some pretty what I considered Hollywood loudmouths there.
What did you and the other junction, did you all have a name for the group?
Were you junction kids or junction?
I don't know, I just always remember just the junction adjunct, it was called the adjunct there, but
I don't remember us having him.
Some people would laugh about it and say, hey, we're the dumb kids, you know, that are trying to improve, but we'd all already been admitted to Texas A&M, and there was no requirement to come.
And some of the, of course, some of the people that came were in the tops of their high school class and definitely went on to bigger and better things.
What did you all do for fun?
Well, I think...

know you get down there down the little river there and you go swimming we uh it seemed like most of the time that i remember most of it was geared towards just surviving in school because i think probably the thing that helped me was they they made a very very very big push on keeping you busy very very busy you had lots of homework no matter which of the classes you were taking you had papers like english it seemed like you never got
One paper finished that there wasn't another one that was due.
And I remember going Saturday night so we could go in.
I would go to church on Sunday in Junction.
Seemed like Junction may have been, I don't know, three miles away.
I don't remember how far it was.
I remember we walked one time, but I remember going one night to the rodeo and
And I was a Western music, country music fan, and that's the first time I'd ever seen Jimmy Heap in the Melody Masters.
So I remember that.
And I had grown up around rodeos, so you would, those dances out there on the old tennis court or whatever.
But for some reason, I definitely remember that night.
But there was no real wild partying on Saturday night.
I think I came out from maybe a little different environment from a lot of kids.
I came from a pretty...

pretty conservative life, even though I hung around rodeos, and sure I would, the typical kid that would go out and drink, but I was not what you'd, as far as drinking beer, but I was not a partier, you know, from that standpoint, you know.
Now, I've heard lots of the stories of the guys that would go out, and I was shy, S-H-Y with a capital, S-H-Y.
All right, so you went six weeks, then went home.
Went home.
I could have stayed for the 12, but I figured, you know, I was ready to get.
And I worked five summers in the oil field, and I came back and worked those second six weeks.
Then when you came to the campus to enroll, how did you get here?
I got a ride with one of those six of us from Jacksboro, a gentleman named Bill Sparks.
I remember it.
very well.
I had one footlocker.
I got off over there in front of Dorm 2.
That's Briggs Hall.
And the guardroom, the Corps Staff guardroom was there.
Put my footlocker down there.
And all of a sudden, a guy named Bill Reagan was the first sergeant, this guy that looked very sharp and had khakis on starch.
And he said, anybody here in A Veterinary Company?
And
And I was going to be in a veterinary company, so I got there just in time to leave my footlocker there.
And I joined in, and we marched over to Sully.
And as he said, we were the first unit in 58 to polish Sully.
And I remember that very well, because I had a yellow.
polo golf shirt and a pair of black slacks, and I ruined both of them.
But we were the first unit to polish Sully that day.
Now, how did you get assigned to that unit?
There was a guy, class of 58, that brought us down the year before.
He was here, and we came down, and he was rooming with a guy named Jerry Gleason, and they had just formed the veterinary company.
I might say that...
The first year I was here at Texas A&M 58 to 59 was the last year that they had branch training in the ROTC as far as the Army.

They did have Air Force and Army ROTC, but if you wanted to go into transportation, artillery, quartermaster, air defense, whatever, infantry, you basically went into those companies and you signed up for that.
Well, I thought
I wanted to be a veterinarian, and so I ended up in a veterinary company.
And y'all were what?
Dormitory two, fourth floor.
And describe how you got it.
How were you assigned a room?
I was assigned a room, which was just like the rooms they have now, except we didn't have air conditioning.
Air conditioning is
And I'm sure this has been told 1,000 times, but you would hope that the guy across the hall, the room would open their window, and you'd open your window, and maybe you'd get a little breeze.
But I was assigned room 423.
I remember that room well.
I came back to teach ROTC here, and I remember going up to that room, dorm two, and two sophomores were in the room and went in there.
And they were doing a biology project, and they had a fish in the sink.
And I just thought that was very appropriate.
That's Fish Henderson's room.
I got ready to leave, and they said, sir, are you going to come back?
And I said, well, I might drop in someday.
Why?
And he said, they said, well, if you are, we're going to change rooms with the freshmen.
So I thought that was kind of humorous.
But I was assigned a roommate.
I had four roommates the first semester.
Three of them left school before the semester was over.
I ended up rooming the rest of my
time with another freshman from Big Springs who did not have a penny, worked as a waiter.
And later on, he ended up getting his PhD and teaching at a junior college.
So I think that set the example of what A&M could do for people that were really, we wore the same clothes, ate the same food.
But second semester, we roomed together the whole semester.
Why did those others leave?
I think the first one left the third week we were here, and I think he came from a completely different background than I did.
He came down here in a new car and had been a partier, was from down near Baytown.
And he just didn't like the structure we had of being a freshman.
And you could call it harassment.
Some people referred to it as hazing.
Maybe another term could be good training.
Another one just was definitely homesick.
And I had gone to Philmont Scout Ranch with him.
His father had been an assistant scoutmaster out of the Dallas area.
And we had gotten a bus together from our council.

interesting that he would come then end up being my roommate and he left and the third one he just after thanksgiving he was flunking everything and he was ready to go home i will tell you that i came down here and if i remember right i weighed i weighed 185 pounds i thought i was six foot thought i was in pretty good shape and as i say i'd worked in

the last six weeks in the oil field and I ended up at Thanksgiving I was flunking two courses and I weighed about 159 so I had quite a few views of going home also but but I had at least having gone to Junction I had made some extra grades and so
What advice did your grandmother or anybody else in the family, what advice did anybody give you as you left home?
I don't think I got any advice.
I just came and since then, my father remarried when I was a senior in high school, and my stepmother has said,
three or four times since that.
And she came from a family that stressed education, and she had been a teacher.
But she's always said that when I came home, I admitted to her that I was scared to death, and I didn't think I would make it.
And since then, I've been fortunate enough to continue to go to school and many military schools.
And I think I've done very well academically, but maybe I needed that hurdle to get over.
Do you remember what that first year cost?
What kind of financing?
No, I don't really remember.
I should, but... Did you pay part of it?
I paid part of it, but my father pretty well covered it.
It wasn't very expensive, though.
I think one of the things that made it very reasonable back then was you could come here, our uniforms were furnished, all the clothes were furnished.
I don't ever remember having a sports coat
hanging in the closet until my senior year.
Or feeling that you needed to.
Didn't need it, no.
I did, I will say, answer one of your questions.
I came from, again, what I consider a small town where there's always lots of pressure.
I did have 12 years perfect attendance in Sunday school when I started down here my freshman year.
And I continued that until the Rice Corps trip in Houston, and it was the first time that I'd missed Sunday school.
But I think my upbringing was such that
right and wrong and respect for others, I hope.
And your academic schedule, how did you, that first semester, did you...
I looked in the catalog and it had a pre-vet curriculum with about 18 hours and
You know, all I can say is it was a tough, tough go chemistry.
Remember I mentioned earlier, that's one of them I made 70 in.
Well, I wasn't for very...
But the problem I had, the real problem that I had, and I have taught classes, freshmen, how to study and how to succeed in college, my biggest problem was two things.
Number one, I think, is what...

is preached to you today and it's still true is is I didn't know how to study didn't have any idea how to study I would sit in class and daydream you know or something and the second is I had no concept of managing my time even though maybe what I did learn in the scouts helped me more than I thought but but I was very very ill prepared because I fit into the core the mold of the core where all of a sudden
whatever that sophomore wanted me to do or whatever became more important than the school work.
As you look back, are there some teachers from that first year or so that were important or advisors?
I think the basic division, Mr. Curley was a shining example of help, and I had him later in graduate school as a professor.
I think
Most of my help from professors, though, really started my junior year.
Because the first two years, it seemed like I was more just in the core style life here.
And I didn't really turn for help.
I just played the game.
I think, as somebody asked me one time, what did I major in?
And our mutual friend, we were sitting
at the Shamrock when I came in in 67 for the Rice game.
And in fact, Bones Irwin asked me, said, at that time, I think I was a captain.
He said, Captain Henderson, what did you major in?
And your friend McCandless said, freshman chemistry, which was a little bit of truth.
Because the first two years, I didn't know.
All right, but that first semester, did you pass everything?
No.
Chemistry, went down in chemistry, and that was a four-hour course.
And so I... Who taught, do you remember who taught it then?
Alexander.
Did he have a nickname?
I'm not sure that he had a nickname, but most of the other professors did.
I had Alexander more than once.
In fact, Sally and I stopped in an antique store the other day, and the lady there got to talking about her brother-in-law.
I was from A&M, and did I know a Dr. Alexander?
I said, yes, I did.
You're doing quite well.
That's where I stopped the conversation.
Nice guy.
But we were also in chemistry, which was a shock.
That was the big class that I was in where, you know, my goodness, you had so many.
And then lab was very demanding, and I'm going to quit talking about how I wasn't prepared because...
As I say, it took me a little while, and then I think I finally got over that.
Your first days as a fish, describe the dormitory life, the routine, if there was hazing or whatever it might be called.
Well, I was in a good unit, a veterinary company.
I was fortunate enough to be the guy later on to be responsible, basically, I guess, for overseeing the building and then running of the Core Center.
And one of the first things I did when we put the guidons around, and you see them now inside the Core Center, is right outside my door is hanging a veterinary guidon, which is a replica of it.
But it was a good unit, a lot of good memories.
Most of the guys there.
had no intentions of being in the Corps.
In 1958, they made the Corps compulsory again, so Ben's the only vet school for three states at that time, if I remember right.
We had a lot of guys from as far away as Parrington, all over, having to take a pre-vet, which was a three-year program.
They had no intentions of being in the Corps of Cadets.
But they got down here and found out if they were going to be at A&M, they had to be in the Corps of Cadets.
So that year, it was kind of interesting.
We had probably 20 sophomores and probably started off with 70-something freshmen.
So we were different than all of the other units.
In fact, the next year, they came up with two units, two vet units, because you had more students than you could actually manage from the leadership role and accomplish anything, I think.
So I was in a good unit from the standpoint of not having, let's say, two sophomores that were on my back.
Sure, I had sophomores that were on my back or whatever.
It wasn't just, they also had about six other freshmen that each sophomore was involved with.
You didn't mention any juniors or seniors.
Sat on a table with Ted Harwood.
who's a veterinarian now in San Antonio.
And he was a pretty strict guy, but I can remember him very well.
In fact, I was very fortunate.
This past year, I got to speak at the reunion for the class of 60.
And I'm really looking forward to next year talking to the class of 61, who was
the class that was sophomores when I was a freshman.
But we had most of the people that were in their sophomore year in a veterinary company
We're trying to get into vet school, so grades were emphasized.
I had lots of fish buddies that told so many war stories.
We thought we had it very tough.
As I said, I lost a lot of weight.
I think a lot of that was coming from worrying a lot.
But I got along with, I think,
upperclassmen from the standpoint I was very active in intramurals.

I played a number of sports and back then intramurals was very, very important and which was probably the turning point in my career at A&M because I ended up being a sophomore intramural manager and a junior and then there was four senior intramural managers for the entire campus and I was one of those and so that was probably what my real interest was and still even though
I graduated, I never really put much emphasis on academics.
Did you all have less, in effect, less of the core traditions
that first year or so.
Oh, yes.
I'd hate to admit it to anybody that was in my outfit, but we didn't catch as much, pardon the expression, the old Army hell.
Oh, sure, I stayed up all night polishing floors or things like that.
But I can truthfully say that nobody ever took a board to me.
I'm going out to eat this Friday night with probably my best friend now out of my class.

He was put down, he was in the medical company, which was on the third floor, but he was put down next to an Italian staff and was a freshman for two juniors, which I better not mention their name because you'd know both of them here around A&M now still.
But he had...
